Whales are important in mitigating climate change because they are a key part of the ocean's natural carbon and nutrient cycles, which play a critical role in regulating the Earth's climate and supporting life on our planet. That‚Äôs why it is vital to protect these marine mammals.

Marine Ecosystem Balance: Whales also help to maintain balance in marine ecosystems by feeding on large numbers of smaller animals. This helps to prevent overpopulation of certain species, which can cause ecological imbalances.

Carbon Sequestration: Whales are known as carbon sinks as they store carbon in their body mass and accumulate carbon all throughout their life. When they die, their bodies sink to the ocean floor, taking the carbon with them, which helps to reduce the amount of CO2 from above.

Nutrient Cycling: They feed on krill and other small fish, and then excrete nutrient-rich waste that feeds phytoplankton. The increased growth of phytoplankton results in more carbon being absorbed by the ocean, thus reducing the amount of CO2 in the atmosphere.

In conclusion, climate change is a complex and urgent issue that requires collective action at all levels. By working together to reduce our emissions and protect our planet, we can create a more sustainable and resilient world.
The urgency of addressing climate change cannot be overstated. We must act now to reduce our greenhouse gas emissions and protect our planet for future generations.

Climate change also disproportionately affects marginalized communities, such as low-income and indigenous communities. Addressing climate change requires a just transition that takes into account these communities and their needs

However, addressing climate change requires collective action and international cooperation. This includes agreements such as the Paris Agreement, which aims to limit global warming to well below 2¬∞C above pre-industrial levels.
Governments have a crucial role to play in addressing climate change through policies such as carbon pricing, renewable energy mandates, and regulations on emissions from industry.
Businesses can also play a role in addressing climate change by reducing their emissions and adopting sustainable practices.
Individuals can make a difference by reducing their carbon footprint through actions such as driving less, using energy-efficient appliances, and eating a plant-based diet.

However, there are many things we can do to address climate change. This includes reducing our greenhouse gas emissions, transitioning to renewable energy, and protecting and restoring ecosystems that absorb carbon.
The impacts of climate change are widespread and severe, including rising temperatures, sea level rise, more frequent and severe natural disasters, and threats to food security and public health.

Between these three elements, and to find innovative and collaborative solutions that can create a more sustainable and resilient future for all.

It also means recognizing the need for transformative change and systemic shifts in the way we live, work, and interact with the environment.Ultimately, the success of any efforts to address climate change in Africa will depend on our ability to strike a balance.

This means designing policies and interventions that simultaneously promote adaptation, mitigation, and resilience, and taking into account the unique contexts and needs of different communities and ecosystems.

Conversely, a focus on mitigation at the expense of adaptation can leave vulnerable communities and ecosystems exposed to the immediate impacts of climate change. To navigate this complex landscape, it is crucial to adopt an integrated approach that recognizes the interdependence
There is a risk that prioritizing adaptation over mitigation can perpetuate dependence on fossil fuels and delay the transition to renewable energy sources.

Resilience, meanwhile, aims to enhance the ability of communities and ecosystems to recover from climate-related shocks and stresses.The challenge lies in finding ways to integrate these approaches in a way that maximizes their effectiveness and addresses the root causes.

Adaptation involves building the capacity of communities and ecosystems to cope with the impacts of climate change, such as droughts, floods, and storms. Mitigation focuses on reducing greenhouse gas emissions and limiting the severity of climate change in the long term.

In conclusion, games for impact are a powerful tool for creating positive social and environmental change. By engaging players in fun and interactive ways, they can inspire action and help create a better world

If you're interested in games for impact, there are many resources available to help you get started. Nonprofits and social impact ordianizations are increasingly turning to games as a tool for creating change.

Despite these challenges, games for impact have proven to be an effective tool for creating positive change. They can engage and educate players, create empathy and understanding, and encourage real-world action.

Another challenge is designing games that are both engaging and effective. Games that are too heavy handed or preachy may turn off players, while games that are too simplistic may not effectively communicate the issue.
However, games for impact also face some challenges. It can be difficult to measure their impact and effectiveness, and to ensure that players take real-world action as a result of playing the game.

Games for impact can also be used to encourage players to take real-world action on issues. For example, games that simulate environmental disasters can encourage players to take action to reduce their carbon footprint and protect the environment.

Another benefit of games for impact is that they can create empathy and understanding for people from different backgrounds and perspectives. By putting players in the shoes of others, they can develop a deeper understanding of the issues facing those communities.

Games for impact can also be used to educate players on complex issues in a fun and interactive way. By presenting information in a game format, players are more likely to remember and apply what they ve learned.

One of the main benefits of games for impact is that they can engage and motivate players to take action on important issues. By making the issues more tangible and interactive, players are more likely to care about and act on them
Games for impact can be used in a variety of contexts, from education and activism to healthcare and corporate social responsibility. They can be played online, on mobile devices, or in-person.

The largest sources of global GHG emissions are energy-related emissions from burning fossil fuels for electricity, transportation, and industry, as well as emissions from agriculture, land use, and waste management.
The United States was the second-largest emitter with approximately 4.9 GtCO2e or about 11% of global emissions. Global GHG emissions in 2019 were indeed around 59 GtCO2e, as you mentioned.

According to the latest available data from the Global Carbon Project, China's greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions in 2019 were approximately 14.1 gigatons of carbon dioxide equivalent (GtCO2e), which is about 30% of global emissions.
"You are correct that the numbers I provided in my previous answers were inconsistent. I apologize for the confusion and any misinformation that may have caused.
When challenged, here is what ChatGPT said:

It seems likely that it served up numbers that encompassed different GHG sources, i.e. possibly including land use emissions in one set of numbers and ignoring them in the other.  In any event, I was surprised that Chatgpt provided internally inconsistent answers.

However, it then gave global GHG emissions for 2019 at 59.1 gigatons - that of course does not plausibly match up with the numbers and percentages for the US and China.  Based on the 2019 US and China  numbers, global emission should be to 36 gigatons.
This seemed plausible (and was close to what I found when checking the Global Carbon Project website directly).

In terms of absolute number, it also indicated that China's 2019 emissions were 10.17 gigatons of carbon dioxide carbonequivalents and US emissions in 2019 were 5.41 gigatons (based on information from the Global Carbon Project).

Maybe it's time we also give more importance to social sciences (and humanities) in the way we tackle climate change. After all, humans caused climate change, and it will take human behaviours to do something about it too. #climatechange

Overland and Sovacool (2020); "Between 1990 & 2018, the natural & technical sciences received 770% more funding than social sciences for research on issues related to climate change. Only 0.12% of all research funding was spent on the social science of climate mitigation."

According to @DeSmog, "From 1990 to 2018, the natural and physical sciences received a total of US$40 billion (for climate change research) compared to only $4.6 billion for the social sciences and humanities."

We can have all the data about projections and carbon budgets but dealing with humans, communities, human behaviours is a different matter. There are already some good social sciences research projects on climate change that are funded. But the funding is skewed. Data below.

If we want to change the world, we need to take the whole world with us. And for that we need the social sciences. The fields of psychology, media and communications, development, etc. are just as important as the hard sciences.

If we can't even convince communities (such as in Oxford) of why 15 minute cities are important (and how it is not a way of governments to control them) then how can we convince bigger populations to support even bigger decarbonisation strategies?

We are dealing with humans whose behaviours & decisions are dictated by many factors. As I see it, continuous disinformation about climate change and climate policy (which might be funded by big oil) & people believing in these can stop implementation of decarbinosation policies.

I see a lot of funding on the hard sciences. And we can get all the data we need to show why we need to decarbonise. But if the people, the very communities we wish to change, do not believe in it and are up in arms about it, what do we do then?
